**Alternatively**, if you cannot create those classes, use a dynamic proxy or a mock class with a custom class loader that overrides getName():

```java
package com.google.gson.internal;

import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;

class ReflectionAccessFilterHelperTest {

  @Test
  void testIsAnyPlatformType_androidType() {
    Class<?> androidClass = createClassWithName("android.mock.Class");
    assertTrue(ReflectionAccessFilterHelper.isAnyPlatformType(androidClass));
  }

  @Test
  void testIsAnyPlatformType_kotlinPackage() {
    Class<?> kotlinClass = createClassWithName("kotlin.SomeClass");
    assertTrue(ReflectionAccessFilterHelper.isAnyPlatformType(kotlinClass));
  }

  @Test
  void testIsAnyPlatformType_kotlinxPackage() {
    Class<?> kotlinxClass = createClassWithName("kotlinx.SomeClass");
    assertTrue(ReflectionAccessFilterHelper.isAnyPlatformType(kotlinxClass));
  }

  @Test
  void testIsAnyPlatformType_scalaPackage() {
    Class<?> scalaClass = createClassWithName("scala.SomeClass");
    assertTrue(ReflectionAccessFilterHelper.isAnyPlatformType(scalaClass));
  }

  @Test
  void testIsAnyPlatformType_otherPackage() {
    Class<?> otherClass = createClassWithName("com.example.SomeClass");
    assertFalse(ReflectionAccessFilterHelper.isAnyPlatformType(otherClass));
  }

  private static Class<?> createClassWithName(String name) {
    return new Class() {
      @Override
      public String getName() {
        return name;
      }
    }.getClass();
  }
}
```

But since Class is final, the above won't work. Instead, use a proxy or a custom interface for the test, or a simple wrapper class with a getName method.

